Bombard to the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the main assets of American President Barack Obama.
It seems today, however, that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After stating last March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama would lose face if he does not react strongly to the murder of over 1,000 civilians, attributed to the Syrian regime, using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama resort to such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
American Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of gas "a moral obscenity."
But torturing children, who were the precursors of the civil war two years ago, is just as bad.
Is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemicals than to bomb them, shoot them, or starve them to death?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, especially nuclear bombs, certainly cause more damage and do so more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing about 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb at Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, notably defended by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, argues that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and return to "more mundane means of killing his people."
In my opinion, that doesn't make sense.
The issue is surely the massacre, not the methods used.
In all cases, moral indignation, however justified it may be, is not a sufficient reason for going to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese people during the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds—with the support of the United States.
Is this therefore a legal question? The use of chemical weapons constitutes a clear violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, which it is a party to.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he must be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, by the way, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a policy easily defensible.
One could however argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are killed en masse?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should we draw the line?
How many murders constitute genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or is the number not taken into account?
A genocide is after all a matter of intention; there is a will to kill or to persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
To answer this implies asking oneself: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the action of the ICTY, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (such as Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
Nobody would consider launching missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or to enforce international laws and conventions related to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
She is not a great power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is by no means certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a broader conflict.
In fact, some supporters of American intervention—both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks"—seem to desire the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama probably established a link in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, can we expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they were not intended to overthrow the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile would make the United States a direct participant in this war, triggering a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly prudent.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
That is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
It might even be Obama's own view, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the U.S. Congress the authority to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relations with Congress have not been easy.
But he needs it more than ever today to cover his back.
